class Solution {
    public int numberOfWays(int n, int x) {
        int mod = (int) (1e9 + 7);
        int[] dp = new int[n + 1];
        dp[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; (int) Math.pow(i, x) <= n; i++) {
            int num = (int) Math.pow(i, x);
            for (int j = n; j >= num; j--) {
                dp[j] = (dp[j] + dp[j - num]) % mod;
            }
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n * m) where m is the number of unique integers whose xth power is less than or equal to n
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Dynamic programming is used to efficiently count the number of ways to express n as the sum of the xth power of unique positive integers. The key insight is to iterate over the possible unique integers and update the dp array accordingly, ensuring that the count is computed modulo 10^9 + 7 to avoid overflow.
